1496
01:10:55,264 --> 01:10:57,858
I finally got
what's called agoraphobia.

1497
01:10:57,967 --> 01:11:02,165
It's when you can't
go out of the house.

1498
01:11:02,271 --> 01:11:04,432
We had a big old farmhouse

1499
01:11:04,540 --> 01:11:06,838
with a river on one side
and woods on the other.

1500
01:11:09,879 --> 01:11:15,078
And we thought that was, like,
a natural barrier to paparazzi.

1501
01:11:15,184 --> 01:11:17,118
But they would just
put on fisherman boots

1502
01:11:17,219 --> 01:11:18,811
and just wade
right through that river.

1503
01:11:21,791 --> 01:11:24,954
I remember one time a woman
came on our property,

1504
01:11:25,061 --> 01:11:26,756
ignored
the "no trespassing" signs,

1505
01:11:26,862 --> 01:11:28,625
and she was just gawking
in the window,

1506
01:11:28,731 --> 01:11:29,720
like, trying to get up

1507
01:11:29,832 --> 01:11:32,562
to see what Joyce McKinney
looked like.

1508
01:11:32,668 --> 01:11:34,260
It went on like that for years.

1509
01:11:38,207 --> 01:11:41,074
I could barely get out
to go feed the horses.

1510
01:11:49,151 --> 01:11:51,085
So finally, I got me
this big old guard dog.

1511
01:11:51,187 --> 01:11:53,621
His name was Tough Guy.

1512
01:11:53,723 --> 01:11:55,520
He was a huge dog.
He weighed about 150 pounds.

1513
01:11:55,625 --> 01:11:56,853
Solid muscle.

1514
01:11:56,959 --> 01:12:00,326
Pit bull mastiff bulldog.
Jaws like a alligator.

1515
01:12:00,429 --> 01:12:02,329
And I just put him right
out in the front yard like,

1516
01:12:02,431 --> 01:12:04,865
"Come on, boys.
Come on."

1517
01:12:07,837 --> 01:12:11,295
One day, he got bee-stung.

1518
01:12:11,407 --> 01:12:13,602
These two women
that worked at the pharmacy

1519
01:12:13,709 --> 01:12:16,234
who didn't like me
decided that it'd just be a hoot

1520
01:12:16,345 --> 01:12:18,506
to add a zero onto
that Prednisone prescription

1521
01:12:18,614 --> 01:12:19,808
for Joyce McKinney's guard dog.

1522
01:12:19,915 --> 01:12:21,075
Wouldn't that be funny?

1523
01:12:21,183 --> 01:12:22,741
Probably drive him nutty,
wouldn't it?

1524
01:12:22,852 --> 01:12:25,719
Well, it drove him
more than nutty.

1525
01:12:25,821 --> 01:12:29,518
The capillaries
in his brain exploded.

1526
01:12:29,625 --> 01:12:32,924
But not before he attacked me.

1527
01:12:33,029 --> 01:12:34,690
He didn't know who I was.

1528
01:12:34,797 --> 01:12:37,231
He amputated...
I can't raise this arm up.

1529
01:12:37,333 --> 01:12:40,029
But he amputated my left arm.

1530
01:12:40,136 --> 01:12:41,763
He tore off three fingers
on this hand.

1531
01:12:41,871 --> 01:12:44,396
He ripped my intestines out
of my stomach wall.

1532
01:12:44,507 --> 01:12:47,032
He shredded my knee

1533
01:12:47,143 --> 01:12:49,976
from my right kneecap
to my ankle.

1534
01:12:50,079 --> 01:12:52,411
I was bleeding to death.

1535
01:12:52,515 --> 01:12:53,982
I was dying.

1536
01:12:57,386 --> 01:12:58,751
A few months before this,

1537
01:12:58,854 --> 01:13:01,220
I had found a little dog
by the side of the road

1538
01:13:01,323 --> 01:13:02,483
going through garbage cans.

1539
01:13:02,591 --> 01:13:03,922
I named him Booger.

1540
01:13:04,026 --> 01:13:05,721
And Booger
was a little pit bull.

1541
01:13:06,729 --> 01:13:08,458
I hit the brakes,
and I backed up,

1542
01:13:08,564 --> 01:13:11,328
and I got out, and I said,
"Could you use a friend?

1543
01:13:11,434 --> 01:13:13,402
"I could use a friend too.

1544
01:13:13,502 --> 01:13:16,232
Okay, I'm a softie.
Get in the car."

1545
01:13:16,338 --> 01:13:17,362
So he went...

1546
01:13:19,141 --> 01:13:22,668
He had a little five-beat
musical bark, Booger did.

1547
01:13:22,778 --> 01:13:24,439
Booger, Booger, Booger.

1548
01:13:24,547 --> 01:13:25,673
I had taken him home with me,

1549
01:13:25,781 --> 01:13:28,215
not realizing that he was
gonna be famous someday

1550
01:13:28,317 --> 01:13:31,445
or that he would save my life
or change the lives... my life

1551
01:13:31,554 --> 01:13:34,216
and the lives of so many people.

1552
01:13:34,323 --> 01:13:36,951
The night that this big mastiff
attacked me, the guard dog,

1553
01:13:37,059 --> 01:13:38,651
I got next door
to where Booger was.

1554
01:13:38,761 --> 01:13:40,251
I said, "Help me, Booger,"
and Booger shot out,

1555
01:13:40,362 --> 01:13:42,091
and he jumped on that other dog
and pulled it off of me.

1556
01:13:43,532 --> 01:13:45,090
It was a fight to the death,
and I thought,

1557
01:13:45,201 --> 01:13:46,998
"Poor little Booger,

1558
01:13:47,103 --> 01:13:49,537
he's gonna give himself
in a Christlike love for me."

1559
01:13:50,606 --> 01:13:52,369
When I came home
from the hospital,

1560
01:13:52,475 --> 01:13:54,807
he sat on the bed beside me,
and we healed together,

1561
01:13:54,910 --> 01:13:56,571
and we formed a bond,
a friendship.

1562
01:13:58,514 --> 01:14:02,507
Booger was a very special dog.

1563
01:14:02,618 --> 01:14:05,781
Not only was he
a licensed service dog,

1564
01:14:05,888 --> 01:14:07,879
but one day he just got up
and unlocked the door,

1565
01:14:07,990 --> 01:14:10,686
and then he started
dialing 911 with his paw.

1566
01:14:10,793 --> 01:14:12,260
He had a big button phone.

1567
01:14:12,361 --> 01:14:13,487
And I'd say, "Booger, help!

1568
01:14:13,596 --> 01:14:15,621
Dial 911."
He'd go, whomp!

1569
01:14:15,731 --> 01:14:16,857
"Booger, I need a towel.

1570
01:14:16,966 --> 01:14:18,490
Go get me a towel
out of the dryer, buddy."

1571
01:14:18,601 --> 01:14:20,330
He'd go in there into the dryer
and get me a towel.

1572
01:14:20,436 --> 01:14:22,370
"Hey, Booger, get me a pop
out of the refrigerator."

1573
01:14:22,471 --> 01:14:25,565
And he'd go get me one,
and he'd so gently carry it

1574
01:14:25,674 --> 01:14:27,699
so he wouldn't burst it
with his teeth

1575
01:14:27,810 --> 01:14:29,607
and drop it in my lap.

1576
01:14:37,386 --> 01:14:38,910
He got me through
that tough time.

1577
01:14:39,021 --> 01:14:42,081
For ten years, he was my helper.

1578
01:14:42,191 --> 01:14:45,126
My beloved old friend Booger
passed away in my arms

1579
01:14:45,227 --> 01:14:47,821
of cancer in April of 2006.

1580
01:14:47,930 --> 01:14:50,057
I tried everything
in the world to save him.

1581
01:14:50,166 --> 01:14:52,532
I took him to every
veterinary hospital I could.

1582
01:14:52,635 --> 01:14:54,000
I said, "You can't die, buddy.

1583
01:14:54,103 --> 01:14:55,866
"You're all I have.
We're a package deal.

1584
01:14:55,971 --> 01:14:57,962
You can't die."

1585
01:14:58,073 --> 01:15:00,667
That was the last command
I gave him, "You can't die."

1586
01:15:00,776 --> 01:15:04,872
And he looked at me as if he
didn't want to disappoint me.

1587
01:15:04,980 --> 01:15:06,971
And those eyes,
with age-old wisdom,

1588
01:15:07,082 --> 01:15:12,349
those dark brown eyes
looked at me like, "Don't worry.

1589
01:15:12,454 --> 01:15:16,550
I'll see you again.
This is not the end for us."

1590
01:15:17,226 --> 01:15:18,318
I just wanted to go to heaven,

1591
01:15:18,427 --> 01:15:20,156
and I thought God
would just have Booger there

1592
01:15:20,262 --> 01:15:21,388
on a cloud for me or something.

1593
01:15:21,497 --> 01:15:23,795
And I'd had such a sad life,
you know,

1594
01:15:23,899 --> 01:15:25,628
with all the tabloid mess.

1595
01:15:25,734 --> 01:15:28,669
And I thought,
"I just want the hurt to stop.

1596
01:15:28,771 --> 01:15:30,466
And I can't do without him."

1597
01:15:30,573 --> 01:15:32,438
Then I heard about cloning.

1598
01:15:32,541 --> 01:15:34,668
You know, I thought, "Well,
I'll just give it a stab."

1599
01:15:35,678 --> 01:15:37,612
I contacted Dr. Byeong Chun Lee

1600
01:15:37,713 --> 01:15:40,580
and asked him
if it was possible.

1601
01:15:40,683 --> 01:15:42,583
I wrote him a letter in Korean,
translated it,

1602
01:15:42,685 --> 01:15:44,550
and then tracked down
his phone number.

1603
01:15:44,653 --> 01:15:47,144
And he goes,
"I can clone your dog."

1604
01:15:47,256 --> 01:15:48,621
I said, "Are you sure?

1605
01:15:48,724 --> 01:15:52,319
I mean, is it possible
I could have my old boy back?"

1606
01:15:52,428 --> 01:15:54,362
He goes, "I can."

1607
01:15:57,666 --> 01:16:01,329
<i>Do you ever feel like God?</i>

1608
01:16:26,395 --> 01:16:27,885
What their plan was

1609
01:16:27,997 --> 01:16:31,398
is to take a little piece
of tissue from Booger's tummy,

1610
01:16:31,500 --> 01:16:33,127
put it in liquid nitrogen

1611
01:16:33,235 --> 01:16:35,601
for its safe trip back
to Seoul, Korea.

1612
01:16:37,072 --> 01:16:40,439
They flew back with the help
of Homeland Security.

1613
01:16:40,542 --> 01:16:44,069
Homeland Security
guarding these little cells.

1614
01:16:44,179 --> 01:16:45,168
<i>Guarding Booger.</i>

1615
01:16:45,281 --> 01:16:46,646
Well, to me,
it was Spirit Booger.

1616
01:16:46,749 --> 01:16:47,716
That's what we called it.

1617
01:16:47,816 --> 01:16:50,046
It was like an orb of light

1618
01:16:50,152 --> 01:16:52,518
moved along the fuselage
of the plane.

1619
01:16:52,621 --> 01:16:54,646
And people were saying,
"What is that?"

1620
01:16:54,757 --> 01:16:58,386
But I knew.
I knew it was old Spirit Booger.

1621
01:16:58,494 --> 01:17:01,588
I closed my eyes, and I said
a silent prayer, and I said,

1622
01:17:01,697 --> 01:17:04,689
"Oh, Heavenly Father,
please take good care of him."

1623
01:17:04,800 --> 01:17:07,394
And it was like he spoke
to my heart, and said,

1624
01:17:07,503 --> 01:17:09,528
"Don't worry.

1625
01:17:09,638 --> 01:17:11,970
"He's with me, and he's fine.

1626
01:17:12,074 --> 01:17:16,033
"And you, you are going
to be fine too,

1627
01:17:16,145 --> 01:17:17,840
"because I've got Booger 1,

1628
01:17:17,947 --> 01:17:20,279
"but I'm sending you back
Booger 2

1629
01:17:20,382 --> 01:17:22,873
and a little something extra."

1630
01:17:58,754 --> 01:18:00,278
- I get this
long-distance phone call.

1631
01:18:00,389 --> 01:18:02,254
It's Dr. Hong.

1632
01:18:02,358 --> 01:18:05,623
"Miss Brenann, what is best news
I can bring to you?"

1633
01:18:05,728 --> 01:18:08,219
And I said, "We're pregnant?

1634
01:18:08,330 --> 01:18:09,922
We're pregnant!"

1635
01:18:10,032 --> 01:18:11,056
He said, "We are."

1636
01:18:11,166 --> 01:18:16,468
On August the 5th,
I flew to Seoul, Korea.

1637
01:18:32,087 --> 01:18:35,022
Well, I found out what
the little something extra was

1638
01:18:35,124 --> 01:18:37,922
that Heavenly Father
had promised me.

1639
01:18:38,027 --> 01:18:39,551
<i>There were five.
Five?</i>

1640
01:18:39,661 --> 01:18:42,994
Five cloned puppies,
all exactly like Booger,

1641
01:18:43,098 --> 01:18:46,431
five mini Boogers lying there
like little black jelly rolls

1642
01:18:46,535 --> 01:18:48,867
with half the world press
crowding around.

1643
01:18:48,971 --> 01:18:51,531
They just looked like
little tiny mini Boogers.

1644
01:18:51,640 --> 01:18:53,301
It was the strangest feeling.

1645
01:18:57,179 --> 01:18:58,703
The weirdest thing is,

1646
01:18:58,814 --> 01:19:01,009
I was sitting in a hotel
in Seoul, Korea,

1647
01:19:01,116 --> 01:19:03,277
and one of them got up
and opened the door,

1648
01:19:03,385 --> 01:19:04,511
and he was four months old.

1649
01:19:04,620 --> 01:19:07,555
And I just went...

1650
01:19:07,656 --> 01:19:08,782
I thought, "How'd he know that?

1651
01:19:08,891 --> 01:19:10,153
I didn't train them to do that."

1652
01:19:10,259 --> 01:19:12,159
You know, they have
those little refrigerators

1653
01:19:12,261 --> 01:19:15,526
with little wooden doors,
like a cabinet, in hotels.

1654
01:19:15,631 --> 01:19:17,826
And he just reached right up,
got that silver knob,

1655
01:19:17,933 --> 01:19:19,195
and jerked it open
with his teeth

1656
01:19:19,301 --> 01:19:20,427
just like old Booger used to do.

1657
01:19:20,536 --> 01:19:22,003
And then, when one of them
got the leash

1658
01:19:22,104 --> 01:19:23,162
and went over to the door

1659
01:19:23,272 --> 01:19:24,933
and dropped it like,
"Walk me, now,"

1660
01:19:25,040 --> 01:19:27,736
like Booger did,
it blew me away.

1661
01:19:27,843 --> 01:19:30,277
I said, "These are his clones."

1662
01:19:30,379 --> 01:19:32,609
It was $25,000,
if I can remember.

1663
01:19:32,714 --> 01:19:35,774
<i>Well, the original price was,
I believe, $150,000.</i>

1664
01:19:35,884 --> 01:19:37,317
Was it?
God.

1665
01:19:37,419 --> 01:19:38,716
She must like her dogs.

1666
01:19:38,821 --> 01:19:41,847
I don't know.
Some girl.

1667
01:19:41,957 --> 01:19:43,390
It was in all the papers.

1668
01:19:43,492 --> 01:19:47,986
<i>"Dog cloning girl turns out
to be the Joyce McKinney,"</i>

1669
01:19:48,097 --> 01:19:50,861
because she pretended
it wasn't her to start with.

1670
01:19:50,966 --> 01:19:52,934
She called herself
Brenann McKinney.

1671
01:19:53,035 --> 01:19:54,866
Something like Brenann,
was it?

1672
01:19:54,970 --> 01:19:56,699
Berman McKinney,
or something like that.

1673
01:19:56,805 --> 01:19:58,796
I forget what name she used.

1674
01:19:58,907 --> 01:20:01,137
I knew right away it was Joyce.

1675
01:20:01,243 --> 01:20:02,403
<i>Why?</i>

1676
01:20:02,511 --> 01:20:05,036
Well, I think there was
a photograph.

